<TITLE> Greene King sales slow as Christmas disappoints </TITLE>
<TEXT>
 LONDON, Feb 1 (bdnews24.com/Reuters) - Greene King, the brewer of Abbot Ale and Old Speckled Hen, joined the list of British pub firms warning of slowing sales and a tough year ahead on Friday, though it said it was confident of meeting analysts' forecasts. Greene King, which has roughly 2,500 pubs in England and Scotland, said its managed and tenanted pub like-for-like sales had slowed and were now broadly flat for the 38 weeks to Jan. 20, while group margins remained ahead of last year. Last spring the firm's sales had begun briskly, but dreadful summer weather, the introduction of a smoking ban in English pubs and the erosion of consumer confidence have combined to drag sales lower. "The recent trading environment has become more challenging for the pub and beer industry," Greene King said in a statement. "The Christmas and New Year period showed improved trading over previous weeks, but whilst peak days showed growth year on year, trading on other days was more subdued," it added. The brewer, based in Bury St Edmunds, England, is expected to report profit of 144 million pounds ($286.6 million) when it posts full-year results, according to a Reuters poll averaging out the forecasts of 15 analys
